## How to Read History

Before making changes, ALWAYS review what has been tried:
1. `cat results.tsv` — Full experiment log (iteration, score, status, description)
2. `git log --oneline` — Only successful improvements are in the git log
3. `cat autoresearch/results/latest-evaluation.json` — Last evaluation breakdown with per-viewport scores AND source/rendered heights
4. **Read the diff images** — `autoresearch/results/desktop-diff.png` shows pixel-level mismatches in red/yellow. Read this image to see WHERE the visual differences are and target your changes accordingly.
5. `git diff HEAD~1` (if available) — see what the last successful change actually did
6. `cat autoresearch/results/last-reverted.diff` (if exists) — see the exact diff of the last FAILED attempt, so you don't repeat it

If results.tsv shows repeated reverts for similar approaches (e.g., multiple "height" or "padding" attempts), DO NOT try that approach again. Try something fundamentally different.

## How the Evaluator Scores You

After you exit, an immutable evaluator runs. It produces a composite score (0-100):
- **70% weight**: Visual similarity via pixelmatch (desktop 60%, tablet 20%, mobile 20%)
- **30% weight**: Nav completeness (are all {{NAV_ITEM_COUNT}} source nav items present in the rendered HTML?)

**Important**: The evaluator pads images to equal dimensions before comparing. If your rendered header is shorter than the source, the missing rows count as full-row pixel mismatches. **Matching the source header height (~{{HEADER_HEIGHT}}px) is essential for a good visual score.**

The outer loop keeps your changes if the score improves, reverts if it doesn't.

